South Africa&#8217;s rand and government bonds extended losses on Wednesday following political tensions that led to the country&#8217;s debt being downgraded to junk status by S&amp;P Global Ratings earlier in the week.Stocks were firmer, buoyed by resource companies.At 1500 GMT, the rand traded at 13.7700 per dollar, 1.03 percent weaker from its New York close on Tuesday.&#8220;With ministers in and out, that does not bode well with international investors so naturally they would sell off our currency out of fear and concern,&#8221; Afrifocus Securities markets analyst Cheslyn Francis said.South Africa has been in the grip of a political storm after President Jacob Zuma&#8217;s controversial cabinet reshuffle triggered a downgrade that rocked markets. The ruling ANC party backed Zuma, and rejected calls for the president to quitIn fixed income, the yield for the benchmark government bond due in 2026 rose 9 basis points to 9.005 percent.On the stock market, the benchmark Top-40 index was up 0.9 percent firmer at 46,149 points, while the broader All-share index gained 0.6 percent to 52,990.Resource stocks got a lift from a rise in metals prices with diversified miner BHP Billiton the biggest gainer among the blue-chips, rising 5.2 percent to 221.41 rand.Copper prices rose more than 2 percent, on upbeat jobs data from the United States.South African resource firms were buoyed even further, as they earn their revenue in dollars and pay their costs in rand.&#8220;Resource stocks are going to enjoy that&#8230; the weaker rand,&#8221; said Northshore Capital fund manager Mark Loubser.Steinhoff International, a furniture and general retailer with units in Europe, Britain and the U.S., added 4.9 percent to 67.75 rand, also benefiting from the weaker rand.Banks were among the losers as the credit downgrade and lingering political tensions weigh on their business prospects. The banking index fell 2.4 percent to 6,944 points.